<h2>
    Introduction: Why Salmon Fishing Around Portland is World-Class
</h2>
<p>
    Portland, Oregon isn’t just known for its hip culture and beautiful forests—it’s also one of the top spots in the Pacific Northwest for salmon fishing. Nestled between the confluence of major rivers and within reach of pristine coastal waterways, Portland offers a rich blend of urban convenience and wild angling experiences. With runs of chinook, coho, and even chum salmon coursing through these waters, anglers from all over the country find a reason to visit and fish.
</p>
<p>
    Whether you're a seasoned salmon chaser or a first-time fisherman, knowing the <strong>best salmon fishing spots near Portland, Oregon</strong> can make all the difference in your success—and your memories.
</p>
<h2>
    Columbia River – The Crown Jewel of Oregon Salmon Fishing
</h2>
<p>
    The mighty Columbia River is one of the most iconic salmon fishing rivers in the world, and it runs right past Portland. It's a powerhouse for chinook (king) and coho (silver) salmon, with millions of fish returning every year to spawn.
</p>
<h3>
    Bonneville Dam to Astoria Stretch
</h3>
<p>
    The stretch from Bonneville Dam all the way to Astoria is packed with productive fishing zones. Anglers often target areas near Rooster Rock, Kelly Point, and the mouth of the Willamette River. This zone is especially popular during the spring and fall salmon runs.
</p>
<h3>
    When &amp; What to Fish for on the Columbia River
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spring Chinook:</strong> March to May
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fall Chinook:</strong> August to October
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Coho Salmon:</strong> Late August through October
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Trolling herring or spinners behind flashers is a popular technique here, especially in the lower river and estuary regions.
</p>
<h2>
    Willamette River – Urban Angler’s Paradise
</h2>
<p>
    The Willamette River flows right through downtown Portland and offers surprisingly productive salmon fishing right within city limits. This river sees strong spring chinook and coho returns thanks to hatchery programs and ideal spawning conditions.
</p>
<h3>
    Best Access Points Near Downtown Portland
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Sellwood Bridge</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Cathedral Park</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Milwaukie Waterfront Park</strong>
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Drift fishing from the shore or trolling in a small boat can both be effective. The convenience of city access makes the Willamette ideal for a quick after-work fishing session.
</p>
<h2>
    Sandy River – A Local Favorite for Chinook and Coho
</h2>
<p>
    Just 20 minutes east of Portland, the Sandy River is known for its scenic beauty and impressive salmon runs. The river originates from Mount Hood and winds through stunning forestland before meeting the Columbia River.
</p>
<h3>
    Tips for Wading and Drift Fishing
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Use bobber and eggs for chinook.
    </li>
    <li>
        Drift corkies or yarn flies for coho in the fall.
    </li>
    <li>
        Try Dodge Park or Oxbow Park for easy river access.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Water clarity and flow play a big role in success here—watch conditions closely, especially after rainfall.
</p>
<h2>
    Clackamas River – A Family-Friendly Fishing Destination
</h2>
<p>
    Another close-to-Portland gem, the Clackamas River is popular among families and beginner anglers. It supports both wild and hatchery salmon, and the river is manageable by both boat and from the bank.
</p>
<h3>
    Key Parks and Boat Ramps to Launch From
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>High Rocks Park</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Riverside Park in Clackamas</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Carver Boat Ramp</strong>
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    This river is ideal for spring chinook and fall coho. Early morning bite windows yield the best action.
</p>
<h2>
    Nehalem River – A Coastal Gem Within Reach of Portland
</h2>
<p>
    About 90 minutes west of Portland, the Nehalem River flows into Nehalem Bay and offers some of the largest fall chinook in the region. With both tidal and freshwater sections, it offers a variety of techniques and challenges.
</p>
<h3>
    Tidal Fishing vs. Upper River Strategies
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Tidal Zone:</strong> Troll herring or spinners.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Upper River:</strong> Back-bounce eggs or drift fish with jigs.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Timing is everything on the Nehalem. Aim for days following the first fall rains.
</p>
<h2>
    Wilson River – Fast Water, Big Rewards
</h2>
<p>
    The Wilson River is a favorite among more experienced anglers who enjoy the challenge of fast-moving water and sharp wits. Located near Tillamook, it’s about a two-hour drive from Portland.
</p>
<h3>
    Best Time to Target Salmon on the Wilson River
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Fall Chinook:</strong> Late September through November
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter Steelhead (bonus):</strong> December through March
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Key locations include Mills Bridge and Siskeyville. Wading anglers should be prepared for swift currents.
</p>
<h2>
    Trask River – Salmon and Scenic Beauty Combined
</h2>
<p>
    The Trask River runs through private timberland and into Tillamook Bay. Known for its hatchery coho and big chinook, this river remains under the radar for many Portland anglers.
</p>
<p>
    Try back-bouncing roe or float fishing with jigs in the deeper holes and tail-outs near the hatchery.
</p>
<h2>
    Youngs Bay – Estuary Fishing at Its Best
</h2>
<p>
    Near Astoria, Youngs Bay is a staging ground for fall chinook heading up the Columbia and its tributaries. Troll with herring or plug-cut bait around the mouth for aggressive strikes.
</p>
<p>
    Fishing here peaks in late August and early September, with tidal swings heavily influencing bite activity.
</p>
<h2>
    Gear Essentials for Salmon Fishing in Oregon
</h2>
<p>
    To successfully fish for salmon near Portland, you'll need:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rod:</strong> 8’6” to 10’ medium-heavy action rod
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Reel:</strong> Level-wind reel with strong drag
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Line:</strong> 30-50 lb braided mainline with 12-25 lb fluorocarbon leader
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bait:</strong> Cured eggs, herring, spinners, jigs
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Don’t forget polarized glasses, proper footwear, and a landing net.
</p>
